Replication Analysis

Load and Clean Data

file_path <- "results_prod-6.csv"
raw_lines <- readLines(file_path)
Warning in readLines(file_path): incomplete final line found on
'results_prod-6.csv'
data_lines <- raw_lines[!grepl("^#", raw_lines)]
con <- textConnection(data_lines)
data <- read.csv(
    con,
    header = FALSE,
    fill = TRUE,
    col.names = paste0("V", 1:30),
    stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)
close(con)

# Filter Experimental
# Based on inspection:
# V13: Part_ID, V14: Item_Set, V16: Item_Type ("experimental"),
# V17: Condition1 (Gen/Nom), V18: Condition2 (Match types)
# V19: Correct, V20: Response, V21: RT
clean_data <- data %>%
    filter(V16 == "experimental") %>%
    select(
        Part_ID = V13,
        Item_Set = V14,
        Trial_Order = V15,
        Condition1 = V17, # e.g. Gen/Nom
        Condition2 = V18, # e.g. attractorMatch, targetMatch, etc.
        Correct_Resp = V19,
        Participant_Response = V20,
        RT = V21
    ) %>%
    distinct(Part_ID, Item_Set, Trial_Order, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
    mutate(
        RT = as.numeric(as.character(RT)),
        Response_Binary = ifelse(Participant_Response == "Yes", 1, 0),
        Is_Correct = ifelse(Participant_Response == Correct_Resp, 1, 0),
        # Ensure factors
        Condition1 = as.factor(Condition1),
        Condition2 = as.factor(Condition2)
    )

# Quick check
table(clean_data$Condition1, clean_data$Condition2)

  nom             72      72          72

Descriptive Plots (Dots and Error Bars)

We plot the mean acceptance rate with standard error bars, consistent with the reference style.

desc_stats <- clean_data %>%
    group_by(Condition1, Condition2) %>%
    summarise(
        Mean = mean(Response_Binary, na.rm = TRUE),
        SE = sd(Response_Binary, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(n()),
        .groups = "drop"
    )

ggplot(
    desc_stats,
    aes(x = Condition1, y = Mean, color = Condition2, group = Condition2)
) +
    geom_errorbar(
        aes(ymin = Mean - SE, ymax = Mean + SE),
        width = 0.1,
        position = position_dodge(0.3)
    ) +
    geom_point(size = 3, position = position_dodge(0.3)) +
    # Optional: Add lines if it helps visualization
    # geom_line(position = position_dodge(0.3), alpha=0.5) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1), labels = scales::percent) +
    labs(
        title = "Mean Acceptance by Condition",
        x = "Condition 1",
        y = "Acceptance Rate",
        color = "Condition 2"
    ) +
    theme(legend.position = "top")

Bayesian Analysis

Contrast Setup

We use Helmert-like orthonormal contrasts for the 3-level factor Condition2. Hypothesis: We want to compare levels in a structured way. Assumed Levels: attractorMatch, noMatch, targetMatch.

We define a custom contrast matrix. Contrast 1: attractorMatch vs targetMatch (ignoring noMatch). Contrast 2: noMatch vs Average of (attractorMatch & targetMatch).

(Note: Adjust the matrix below if your hypothesis requires different comparisons)

# Ensure levels are in a known order for the matrix
clean_data$Condition2 <- factor(
    clean_data$Condition2,
    levels = c("targetMatch", "attractorMatch", "noMatch")
)

# Helmert Contrast Matrix (3 levels)
# C1: attractorMatch vs targetMatch
# C2: noMatch vs (attractorMatch + targetMatch)
c_mat <- matrix(
    c(
        -1,
        1,
        0, # C1: target=-1, attr=1, no=0
        -1,
        -1,
        2 # C2: target=-1, attr=-1, no=2
    ),
    ncol = 2
)

# Normalize/Scale if needed (Orthonormal is often best for convergence, but simple integers are interpretable)
# For true Helmert (orthonormal):
# c_mat[,1] <- c_mat[,1] / sqrt(2) # sum of squares = 2
# c_mat[,2] <- c_mat[,2] / sqrt(6) # sum of squares = 6
# Let's keep it simple sum-coded style for interpretation:
# C1 is difference between Attractor and Target
# C2 is 2*No - (Attr+Targ). To make it "Difference between No and Avg(Others)", divide by 2 or use proper scaling.
# We will interpret the raw coefficients carefully or use `hypothesis()` for exact diffs.

colnames(c_mat) <- c("Attr_vs_Targ", "No_vs_Matches")
contrasts(clean_data$Condition2) <- c_mat

# Condition 1 (2 levels) - Simple Sum Coding (+1/-1)
contrasts(clean_data$Condition1) <- contr.sum(2)
colnames(contrasts(clean_data$Condition1)) <- c("Cond1_Diff") # First level vs Grand Mean roughly

print("Contrasts for Condition 2:")
[1] "Contrasts for Condition 2:"
print(contrasts(clean_data$Condition2))
               Attr_vs_Targ No_vs_Matches
targetMatch              -1            -1
attractorMatch            1            -1
noMatch                   0             2

Model Fitting

Fitting a Bayesian logistic regression with random slopes for subjects and items. Note: This might take time.

# We set eval=FALSE by default to prevent accidental long runs during rendering.
# Manually run this chunk to fit.

bf_mod <- bf(
    Response_Binary ~ Condition1 *
        Condition2 +
        (1 + Condition1 * Condition2 | Part_ID) +
        (1 + Condition1 * Condition2 | Item_Set)
)

# Prior usage (generic weekly informative)
priors <- c(
    set_prior("normal(0, 1)", class = "b"),
    set_prior("normal(0, 2)", class = "Intercept"),
    set_prior("lkj(2)", class = "cor")
)

fit <- brm(
    formula = bf_mod,
    data = clean_data,
    family = bernoulli(link = "logit"),
    prior = priors,
    chains = 4,
    iter = 2000,
    warmup = 1000,
    cores = 4,
    seed = 123,
    file = "brms_fit_replication" # Saves to file to avoid refitting
)

Coefficient Plot (Replicating Paper Style)

# Extract estimates
post_summary <- posterior_summary(fit, pars = "^b_") %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    rownames_to_column("Term") %>%
    filter(Term != "b_Intercept")
Warning: Argument 'pars' is deprecated. Please use 'variable' instead.
# Clean Terms for plotting
post_summary <- post_summary %>%
    mutate(
        Term = str_remove(Term, "b_"),
        Term = str_replace(Term, "Condition1", ""),
        Term = str_replace(Term, "Condition2", "")
    )

ggplot(post_summary, aes(y = Term, x = Estimate)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "gray50") +
    geom_point(size = 3) +
    geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = Q2.5, xmax = Q97.5), height = 0.2) +
    labs(
        title = "Bayesian Model Coefficients",
        x = "Estimate (Log Odds)",
        y = "Contrast"
    )
